<HEADLINE>
<P>
D.A. CLEARS OFFICER IN CHICANO PARK SHOOTING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The San Diego County district attorney's office has determined that a San Diego 
police officer was justified in shooting at a man who allegedly took part in a 
drive-by shooting aimed at the officer's car. 
</P>
<P>
In a letter to San Diego Police Chief Bob Burgreen, Dist. Atty. Edwin L. Miller 
cleared Sgt. Adolfo Gonzales of any fault in the shooting, which took place 
July 22 at Chicano Park. 
</P>
<P>
The shooting occurred after Gonzales, a detective in the Police Department's 
gang unit, was notified that someone had been shot at the park. He went to the 
hospital to interview the victim and, on his way back, at about 3:30 a.m., 
picked up his wife, a police dispatcher, from work, then stopped at the park to 
see where the shooting had occurred, Miller's letter says. 
</P>
<P>
At the park, he left his car to look for the site while his wife, who was five 
months pregnant, waited in the vehicle. Gonzales heard gunfire and saw a pickup 
with two people in the back driving by his car and the occupants firing at it, 
the letter says. 
</P>
<P>
Gonzales pulled out his gun and fired two rounds, but the truck left the scene. 
</P>
<P>
The suspects were arrested in September, and one, Guillermo Yanez, told police 
he had been shot at by Gonzales that night. One of the bullets grazed his 
thigh, but did not penetrate his pants, he told police. Yanez was charged with 
attempted murder and firing into an occupied vehicle and is scheduled to go to 
trial Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
Miller said Officer Gonzales was justified in the shooting because California 
law says that a law enforcement officer has the right to use deadly force "when 
he reasonably believes that force is necessary." 
</P>
<P>
"By firing at Sgt. Gonzalez's car with his wife sitting in it, the people in 
the truck put his wife's life in danger. He was legally entitled to use force 
to stop them, and to protect his wife's life," Miller's letter says. 
</P>
<P>
Since 1984, the district attorney's office has reviewed numerous police 
shootings and ruled that each was justified. 
</P>
</TEXT>
