<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD; 
</P>
<P>
'37 CHINESE MASSACRE ADMITTED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
TOKYO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An Imperial Japanese army major left behind an affidavit saying the army dumped 
the bodies of 150,000 Chinese into the Yangtze River during the 1937 "Rape of 
Nanking," the newspaper Mainichi Shimbun reported today. 
</P>
<P>
Maj. Hisao Ohta's 44-page confession is further evidence of the existence and 
the extent of the massacre, which some Japanese right-wing historians and 
politicians say never occurred. 
</P>
<P>
According to Ohta's confession, written while he awaited trial in 1954 in 
Fushun, his army unit dumped the bodies of 19,000 Chinese into the water at the 
Nanking river front over three days starting on Dec. 15, 1937. 
</P>
<P>
A neighboring unit "processed" 81,000 victims at the same time, and elsewhere 
in Nanking, units took care of another 50,000, Ohta's confession, preserved in 
China's Nanking Massacre Memorial Hall, says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief; Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
